{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486940"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"213"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/213"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.08,0.14,0.08,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34651"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/213"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"254"},{"type":"tags","id":"255"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37"},{"type":"contributions","id":"145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8732"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/34651"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department following a head-on motor vehicle accident which occurred at 60km/h. His consciousness is rapidly deteriorating and the decision is made to intubate him in a rapid sequence induction. A cervical spine collar has been applied.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pre-oxygenation for three minutes with bag-valve mask","Stat dose of midazolam","Application of cricoid pressure during intubation","Placement of patient in sniffing position","Ketamine infusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe urgency of this situation, underscored by the patient\u0027s deteriorating conscious level, prompts rapid action. The first step in rapid sequence induction after preparing the patient, equipment, medications, and team members is to \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-oxygenate\u003C/strong\u003E (or conversely, denitrogenate) the lungs with 100% inspired oxygen to extend the safe apnoea time. A bag-valve mask apparatus is the preferred method for pre-oxygenation as it can create an adequate seal between the circuit and the patients airway, thereby delivering 100% FiO2. Typically in a rapid sequence induction, the bag-valve mask apparatus would not be used to assist ventilation. However, if there is desaturation or critical hypoxia, before adequate intubation conditions have been obtained, this device can also be used for assisted ventilation and maintaining oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacing the patient in the \u0027sniffing\u0027 position\u003C/strong\u003E (with neck extended) risks exacerbating any spinal trauma to the patient\u0027s uncleared and unprotected cervical spine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECricoid pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is a somewhat controversial manoeuvre that is commonly practiced in Australia and the USA but infrequently in Europe - the logic is primarily to prevent gastric reflux and aspiration, but evidence of effectiveness in this regard is lacking. When used, cricoid pressure is applied after pre-oxygenation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of hypnotics such as ketamine and midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E also occur after pre-oxygenation. Ketamine is a commonly-used induction agent in this setting, and while midazolam may be used, its time to effect can be prolonged and is often used in patients who are already obtunded as an amnestic rather than for true anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The first step in rapid sequence induction after preparing the patient, equipment, medications, and team members is to pre-oxygenate"],"references":["Bernhard M et al. The First Shot Is Often the Best Shot: First-Pass Intubation Success in Emergency Airway Management. Anesth Analg. 2015; 121(5):1389-93","El-Orbany, M \u0026 Connolly, LA 2010, \u0027Rapid sequence induction and intubation: current controversy\u0027, Anesth Analg, vol. 110, no. 5, May 1, pp. 1318-1325.","Stewart, JC, Bhananker, S \u0026 Ramaiah, R 2014, \u0027Rapid-sequence intubation and cricoid pressure\u0027, Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci, vol. 4, no. 1, Jan, pp. 42-49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"213"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19619"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-04-05T21:35:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-04-05T21:35:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"213"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synon